'''Scouting and Guiding in Anguilla''' exist as branches of the parent organisations in the [[United Kingdom]]. __NOTOC__ ==The Scout Association of Anguilla== {{Infobox WorldScouting | name =The Scout Association of Anguilla | image =Anguilla Branch of The Scout Association.svg | image-size = | caption = | type = | owner = | age = | headquarters = | location =P.O. Box 1167, [[The Valley, Anguilla|The Valley]] | country =Anguilla | coords = | f-date = | defunct = | founders = | founder = | award-for = | members = | chiefscouttitle = Chief Scout | chiefscout = [[Christina Scott]] | chiefscouttitle2 = | chiefscout2 = | chiefscouttitle3 = | chiefscout3 = | website = | affiliation = }}
'''The Scout Association of Anguilla''' operates as a branch of the United Kingdom [[The Scout Association|Scout Association]], due to [[Anguilla]]'s status as a [[British overseas territories|British Overseas Territory]] of the United Kingdom. The Anguillan [[Scout Oath]] and Law, as well as other Scouting requirements, closely follow that of the United Kingdom.
Although the program activities are taken from the British system, Anguilla Scouting is geared to the Caribbean way of life. Training for [[Wood Badge]] and leader training are conducted with the help of British and nearby Caribbean Scout associations. Anguillan Scouts participate in numerous Caribbean camps and events.
In 2015, Governor of Anguilla [[Christina Scott]] was made Chief Scout by the Scouts of Anguilla during a visit by Scouts from Coventry and Warwickshire, United Kingdom. {{cn|date=September 2016}}
==Girlguiding Anguilla== {{Infobox WorldScouting | type = | image = Anguilla Girl Guides 1968.svg | caption= | name = Girlguiding Anguilla | headquarters = | location = | country = Anguilla | f-date = 1933 | founder = | members = 100 | chiefscouttitle = Chief Guide | chiefscout = [[Liz Burnley]] | chiefscouttitle2= Branch Commissioner | chiefscout2= [[Oluwakemi M. Linda Banks]] }}
'''Girlguiding Anguilla''' (formerly ''Anguilla Girl Guide Association'') is a [[Girl Guides|Guiding]] organization in [[Anguilla]], founded in 1933. It is one of the nine branch associations of [[Girlguiding UK]]. It is represented by Girlguiding UK at [[World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts]] (WAGGGS) level and Girlguiding UK's Chief Guide is also Chief Guide for Girlguiding Anguilla. Girlguiding Anguilla is part of the [[Caribbean Link for Guiding]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Face to face with globalization | publisher = [[World Association of Girl Guides and Girl Scouts|WAGGGS]] | date = 2006-06-15 | url = http://western.wagggsworld.org/en/news/389 | accessdate = 2006-10-30 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070629140158/http://western.wagggsworld.org/en/news/389 | archivedate = 2007-06-29 | df = }}</ref>
In 1968, Anguilla issued a set of four postage stamps celebrating the 35th anniversary of Girl Guiding in Anguilla.
The program is a modified form of Guiding in the [[United Kingdom]], adapted to suit local conditions, with the same Promise, and Rainbow, Brownie, Guide and Ranger groups.
